####  	  **Abstract**

Since the advent of Bitcoin, the spread of the second generation of blockchains has developed the development infrastructure of various decentralized applications and excellent security systems to implement them in order to provide an environment in which various smart contacts can be executed according to the user's business environment. However, numerous blockchain projects are still trapped in low and limited interoperability. The provision of liquidity between different chains is limited, and compatibility between native coins and data processing of different layers are also very limited. Cross-chain and cross-rollup communication are essential for enhancing interoperability, scalability, and functionality within the blockchain ecosystem. Users and developers can maximize the utility of their assets by leveraging the unique features of different blockchains and rollups. 

Vision Chain is a modular blockchain protocol powered by a future forward scalability framework with seamless interoperability and strong security guarantees. Vision Chain is a network powered by intent centric interaction model. An intent-centric approach focuses on the intentions behind transactions rather than the specific actions to be performed. By focusing on intents, it's possible to design more user-friendly and intention-revealing transaction constructs, facilitating easier understanding and auditing of cross-ecosystem interactions. We are integrating this intent centric model with account abstraction for the creation of generalized transaction templates that can be interpreted and executed by different blockchain protocols, significantly simplifying the complexity of cross-chain and cross-rollup operations.For this purpose, we provide an Intent Centric Wallet supported by account abstraction through a cross chain intent fusion framework (CCIFF). 

Our cross chain, cross rollup interoperability capability will be powered by the innovative implementation of zero knowledge set based aggregation layer. Major highlight of our blockchain protocol will be the proof of visibility consensus which will be powered by zero knowledge range proofs. The visibility proofs will be the combination of proof of range and proofs of randomness integrated in a recursive manner. The proof of visibility will  be ordered using Homomorphic time lock puzzles. Visibility Proofs will be verified by the Fairness based Sequencer Network powered by Single Secret Leader Election. . 

We will implement the Shuffle Sharding technique together with an Ephemeral State Sharding approach. Our Mempool will be a Cuckoo Hashing based DAG system optimized for speed and scalability. Homomorphic Hashing based data availability sampling method will make our protocol extremely resistant to quantum computer powered adversaries. In summation, the treatise posits that the establishment of proficient cross-chain and cross-rollup communication protocols is vital for the fruition of an entirely interoperable, scalable, and decentralization-focused blockchain ecosystem.

## **2.Technical Key Features**

We have designed the Vision Chain in the creative convergence of following future forward innovations relevant to each important phase of the blockchain transaction lifecycle. 

* A cross chain intent fusion framework powered by account abstraction  
* A secure interoperability layer powered by Zero Knowledge Sets  
* A scalable and secure DAG Mempool powered by Cuckoo Hashing  
* A fair sequencer system powered by Single Secret Leader Election  
* A novel consensus algorithm with VDFs, ZKPs and Time Locks  
* A novel and scalable state sharding technique powered by Verkle Trees  
* A multi purpose zkProver system designed for entire transaction lifecycle  
* A scalable and secure zkVM designed for sharding implementation  
* A secure data availability layer powered by Homomorphic Hashing

The design dynamics of the Vision Chain embodies the expression of modular blockchain architecture. Vision Chain is also an expression of elegant experience design through blending account abstraction and intent based interactions. The combination of account abstraction and intents carves out a digital economy where end users are able to elicit their expectations from blockchain economy in a dynamic manner. Once intents traverse through our cross chain intent fusion framework, the user experiences the power of decentralized intent solvers and diversity of intent execution models. Now the power of zero knowledge set based interoperability layer opens us the gateway of seamless and secure chain connectivity. Once transactions traverse through the interoperability layer, it is added to the Cuckoo Hash based DAG Mempool. DAG approach ensures scalability whereas Cuckoo Hash provides best in class collision resistance and hence minimum possibility of disputes for unconfirmed transactions. Once transactions are stored on the mempool, the shared sequencer network of the vision chain initiates the transaction ordering. The shared sequencers of the vision chain are designed as fair sequencers through a single secret leader election mechanism powered by re-randomizable commitments. The fair sequencers of the vision chain execute the proof of visibility consensus algorithm. Proof of visibility consensus is designed as a zero knowledge density proof powered by the combination of SNARKs and STARKs. They are the privacy preserving representation of the density of transactions from the Mempool. Once the transactions are ordered through the proof of visibility consensus, the shards are generated through a space efficient data structure known as verkle tree. Through verkle trees, an ephemeral shard state is computed. Once shards are generated, it has to be aggregated in the zkVM. We are implementing a type 2 zkVM powered by dynamic cryptographic accumulators. Once the shards are aggregated in the zkVM node, the data availability layer initiates the transaction finality with the layer1. Our data availability layer will be powered by a homomorphic hashing based data availability sampling approach. We would like to provide the finer details of our protocol features in the next sections.

### **2.1. Intent Centric Wallets**

Vision Chain Wallets will be powered by Wallets that use Account Abstraction[^1] for creating secure and seamless smart contract accounts. The user journey begins with an intent centric wallet that empowers the user to express their intent for participating in transactions. The intent solvers in the network will compete to solve the intents. We will implement the Dutch auction method for fair competition between the solvers. Based on the auction result, the successful solver will fetch the intents from the intent specific mempool which will be different from the mempool used by the shared and decentralized sequencers. 

Combining account abstraction and Intent centric wallets in blockchain implementations offers several benefits. Users express their intent (e.g., "send 1 ETH to Alice") instead of dealing with complex transaction details like gas fees and network selection. Users can also define specific conditions for transactions (e.g., "send ETH only if the price reaches $2000"). Wallets can execute complex strategies based on pre-defined intents, like automatic rebalancing or stop-loss orders. By adopting the concept of intent-based applications, our goal is to simplify the complex technical processes that support these actions, focusing instead on fulfilling the user's intended outcome.

#### **2.1.1. Account Abstraction:**

Account abstraction aims to revolutionize how users interact with the blockchain. By decoupling signing and transaction execution, account abstraction utilizes "smart wallets" instead of traditional externally owned accounts (EOAs). These smart wallets, controlled by users' private keys, express their intent. An intent  solver framework translates this intent into a valid transaction. In our implementation we will be deploying a cross chain intent fusion framework as the intent solver. This transaction is then signed by the user and processed through UserOperations, Bundlers, and Paymasters. This separation offers enhanced security as users never expose their private keys directly to the network, and it also allows for greater flexibility in how users interact with the chain, including features like off-chain fee estimation and customizable transaction execution. 

#### **2.1.2. Intent[^2]**

In a traditional model, blockchain transactions are driven by imperative instructions, whereas in the intent centric model, users can express their intentions in a declarative manner which can be realized through a multitude of pathways. The permutations and combinations of these pathways will open up new game theoretic possibilities as well. This will help us to create a dynamic and diligent economy around intents. 

##### ***2.1.2.1. Definition of Intent***

Intent can be defined as a set of declarative constraints that allow users to delegate transaction creation to a specialized network while retaining complete control over the process. Intents focus on outcomes specific to the pathway. Hence intents foster the creation of emergent behaviors in a blockchain network. Intents focus on conditional authorisation rather than code authorisation. Intent holds value only when it can be effectively executed by any entity known as solvers. This compatibility enables an open solver system capable of resolving \`Intent\` based on individual interests.

##### ***2.1.2.2 Need for Intent***

When transmitting the transaction to the vision chain network, it is necessary to transmit the Intent so that it can accurately perform the role of solvers by identifying which Intent is transmitted to process the corresponding trend line through the Wallet's Balance Status. Through this, it is possible to identify and process the presence or absence of a Native token to be used as a gas fee with the most cost-effective processing route.

##### ***2.1.3. Cross Chain Intent Fusion Framework (CCIFF)***

Vision Chain proposes to implement a **cross chain intent fusion framework** (**CCIFF**) that reflects the context and construct of cross chain intents in a further more rigorous manner, aligning with account abstraction. It will be realized using a set of intent initiators, intent interceptors , intent integrators and intent implementers. Intent initiators will pick up the intents from a mempool. Intent interceptors will be realized through cross chain bridges. Intent integrators will streamline intents from the same chain and share it with intent implementers.

##### ***2.1.3.2. Enhanced Process Flow with Paymasters and Aggregators***

1. *Intent Creation: Users create intents without worrying about gas costs or the technicalities of cross-chain operations, thanks to AA’s abstraction layer.*  
2. *Intent Aggregation: Aggregators collect these intents, batching them based on predetermined criteria to optimize execution.*

### **2.2. Zero-Knowledge Based Interoperability Layer**

Once the intents are translated to transactions, they enter the zero knowledge set based interoperability layer. We have come up with an interoperability framework that is powered by chain abstraction and aggregation. The core tenets of these constructions will be zero knowledge proofs and zero knowledge sets. In simple terms, zero knowledge sets are succinct zero knowledge proofs for set membership. When we receive a transaction from different chains, the transactions can be represented as a pair of chain identities and messages.   
![][image4]  
\[ Figure 4\. Limitation of cross chain transactions \]

Zero Knowledge Sets allows a prover to commit to a static collection of pairs ( chain identities, chain messages) that the commitment is succinct and does not leak any information about the committed collection. The prover can prove the statement about the membership / non membership of chain identities in the committed collection with respect to the succinct commitment. The proofs are efficient and do not leak any information about the rest of the committed collection. We will be implementing this approach using the cryptographic primitive known as Append Only Zero Knowledge Set. The key benefit of implementing zero knowledge sets is that it ensures privacy for the chain identities and chain messages from cross chain \- cross rollup transactions. There is no scope for collusion, and corruption in this approach as every actor is unaware of the membership and order of membership in the zero knowledge set.

### **2.3. Cuckoo Hashing[^3] Based DAG Mempool [^4]**

#### **2.3.1. Cuckoo Hashing based DAG Mempool**

Mempool acts as a repository of unconfirmed transactions. The mempool is essentially implemented as an indexed data structure, where the keys are the transaction IDs, and the values are the transactions themselves. It is recommended to use efficient data structures, caching and indexing mechanisms to optimize the mempool. 

Traditional blockchain protocols implement best effort Gossip[^5] Mempool. A transaction submitted to one validator is gossiped to all others. This leads to fine-grained double transmissions: most transactions are shared first by the Mempool, and then the miner / leader creates a block that re-shares them.  

An alternate paradigm has emerged to address the limitations of traditional mempools. It is known as Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)[^6] based Mempool. DAG Mempool implementations have already helped some of the recent protocols to achieve high transaction throughput.  Narwhal Mempool**[^7]** is one of the most successful implementations of this approach. Narwhal provides key-value block store abstraction to read and write transactions with partial orders on the block. The Narwhal mempool uses a restricted DAG called round-based DAG structure. 

DAGs enable parallel processing of transactions, potentially leading to significant performance improvements and faster transaction confirmation times. This is particularly valuable for high-throughput blockchain networks. DAGs can store transactions more compactly compared to queues, potentially reducing the memory requirements for mempool operation, especially in resource-constrained environments. DAGs inherently offer built-in conflict resolution mechanisms due to their directed structure, potentially reducing the risk of orphaned blocks and improving overall network stability.

#### **![][image6]**

			\[ Figure 6\. Transaction represented as DAG \]

We are moving beyond the existing DAG based mempool approaches to a Hashing based DAG mempool. Hashing based DAGs are implemented in some of the DAG based protocols. We are applying a hashing technique known as Cuckoo Hashing for the DAG based Mempool. Cuckoo hashing is a scheme for resolving hash collisions of values of hash functions in a hash table. The process of evicting an existing pair and attempting to insert it using the secondary hash function is called cuckooing. Cuckoo Hashing provides better insertion performance and reduced memory footprint. Especially in dense mempools where most slots are occupied, cuckoo hashing's ability to efficiently handle insertions through the "cuckooing" process could lead to faster transaction inclusion compared to other methods. By eliminating the need for separate overflow buckets used in traditional hashing to handle collisions, cuckoo hashing requires less memory, making it a more suitable option for resource-constrained environments where memory efficiency is critical.

![][image7]

				\[ Figure 7\. Content of Node \]

#### **2.3.2. Technical Advantages**

1. ***Efficiency in Handling Collisions**: Traditional hash tables handle collisions using methods like chaining or open addressing, which can lead to increased search time. Cuckoo Hashing resolves collisions immediately by relocating keys, ensuring constant search time.*  
2. ***High Load Factor**: Cuckoo Hashing maintains high performance even at high load factors, allowing the mempool to store a large number of transactions without significant decreases in performance.*  
3. ***Fast Lookup, Insertion, and Deletion**: The deterministic nature of the lookup, insertion, and deletion operations, all of which are O(1) on average, is crucial for the quick processing of transactions in a blockchain mempool.*  
4. ***Dynamic Resizing**: Like other hash tables, a Cuckoo Hash table can be resized dynamically. This feature is particularly useful for the mempool to adapt to varying numbers of unconfirmed transactions.*  
5. ***Simplicity and Parallelizability**: The simplicity of the Cuckoo Hashing algorithm makes it easy to implement and maintain. Furthermore, because each key has exactly two possible locations, operations on different keys can be easily parallelized, enhancing throughput in a blockchain's mempool.*

### **2.4. Shared Sequencer[^8]**

#### **2.4.1.Organizing Transactions in Rollups for MEV Optimization”**

Sequencing is the process of organizing transactions into blocks. Transactions are organized into blocks based on the associated transaction fees and maximum extractable value (MEV). The concept of shared sequencers comes into play with the introduction of rollups. A shared sequencer in a Rollup refers to a mechanism where multiple Rollup chains or applications utilize a common sequencer for ordering and processing transactions. 

![][image8]  
\[ Figure 8.1. Message Flow Through Shared Sequencers \]

![][image9]

\[ Figure 8.2 Message Flow Through Shared Sequencers \]

#### 

#### **2.4.2.How it works**

Our shared sequencer network will fetch the transactions from the mempool. The sequencer set for every batch of transactions will be selected based on a sequencer selection process known as single secret leader election. The use of a secret leader election mechanism adds an element of security through obscurity. Since the method of selecting the leader is not immediately apparent, it can be harder for malicious actors to predict or manipulate the leader selection process. This process will be secure against attacks from quantum adversaries. 

The leader election process will be based on a mechanism known as **re-randomizable commitments (RRC)**. An RRC scheme must satisfy several properties in order to be secure for use in Single Secret Leader Election.. These properties include binding, unlinkability, and the ability to efficiently test if a re-randomized commitment is to a certain value. This can be constructed using lattice based cryptosystems using integer lattices based on learning with error (LWE) techniques.  The RRC scheme uses a commitment scheme which is additively homomorphic. This means that the commitment scheme can be used to perform computations on ciphertexts without decrypting them first. This allows the parties to compute a commitment to the re-randomization factor, without revealing the factor itself. This ensures that the re-randomization factor remains hidden, even after the commitment has been re-randomized. Once the leader sequencer is selected, the leader sequencer will execute a consensus algorithm known as proof of visibility consensus, which is explained in the next section. 

#### **2.4.3. Technical Advantages**

Security Level advantages

1. **Resistance to Preemptive Attacks**: Since the leader's identity is kept secret until the moment of election, potential attackers cannot target the leader in advance, increasing the network's resistance to attacks.  
2. **Fairness in Leader Selection**: The process ensures a fair and unpredictable selection of the leader, reducing the risk of manipulation or bias in the election process.

Efficiency Level advantages

1. **Faster Consensus**: Streamlined election for selecting the leader using Single Secret Leader Election(SSLE), thus contributing to faster consensus times, thus throughput and efficiency of vision chain is improved.

Decentralization and Trust in untrusted environment

1. **Trustlessness**: The process doesn’t require the participants to trust each other or a single entity during the leader selection process, as the election and verification process are transparent and can also be independently verified by each participant.

#### **2.5.5. Leader & Observer Node** 

In the vision chain network, a leader node is selected in each round through a single secret leader election mechanism and plays a crucial role in executing the shared sequencing model of transaction ordering. The leader node is determined through a **single secret leader election (SSLE)  process,** so no participants know about the leader node in the next transaction. When transaction a is transmitted, Node 1 is committed to "I am the leader of this turn" to process it, and then other nodes will serve as the Observer Nodes. Observer Nodes generates proofs of shard computation capacity ( proof of range ) and proof of shard shuffling capacity ( proof of randomness ) in a secure and scalable manner. Together, the combination of Proof of Range and Proof of Randomness is combined into Proof of Visibility. They also play the role of observers to verify the single secret leader election through verifying the outcome of SSLE..

The role of the Leader Node is assigned sequentially to improve the processing speed of the Proof of Visibility (PoV)..

### **2.5. PoV Consensus**

#### **2.5.1. PoV(Proof of Visibility)**

After PoW(Proof of Work), PoS (Proof of Stake) and PoH (Proof of History) have become the prominent Consensus Algorithms for blockchain transaction verification. We are proposing a new consensus algorithm that leverages some of the key principles of algorithmic randomness, algorithmic fairness and algorithmic recursion.. *Proof of Work (PoW) faces criticism for its high energy consumption, as the mechanism demands significant computational power to mine new blocks and ensure network security, leading to substantial environmental concerns. This requirement for complex computations not only increases transaction times but also limits the number of transactions the network can handle, raising scalability issues. Additionally, the high cost associated with mining equipment and electricity fosters a trend towards mining centralization, undermining the principle of decentralization foundational to blockchain technology. On the other hand, Proof of Stake (PoS) introduces its own set of challenges, notably the concentration of wealth. In PoS systems, those with larger stakes have greater influence, potentially centralizing decision-making power. Furthermore, the "Nothing at Stake" problem poses theoretical security vulnerabilities, as validators could endorse multiple blockchain versions without incurring costs, though practical solutions have been applied to mitigate this issue in various implementations. Proof of History (PoH), a newer concept, introduces complexity in its integration within blockchain architecture, particularly when combined with other consensus mechanisms to maintain network security and efficiency.  PoH was designed for high throughput and scalability in blockchain technologies, faces several challenges including centralization risks, due to the advantage held by nodes with higher computational power, and security concerns stemming from its reliance on timestamping for transaction order. The mechanism's performance is significantly influenced by the hardware used by validators, leading to potential centralization and necessitating frequent hardware updates. Additionally, its technical complexity and the challenges in ensuring accurate timekeeping across the network present barriers to adoption, and scalability may be limited by network bandwidth and the processing capacity of nodes, risking bottlenecks as the network expands.*

**The proof of visibility will be computed based on the computational order to generate the shuffle shards from the DAG Mempool and computational randomness required to generate shuffle sharding. Thus, the proof of visibility will be the combination of proof of range and proof of randomness integrated in a recursive manner in tandem with time lock puzzles. The proof of visibility will  be coupled together with homomorphic time lock puzzles to achieve temporal order. Proof of Visibility generated by the Worker Nodes will be verified by the Leader Node which acts as the Fair Sequencer.** 

![][image12]

\[ Figure 12\. PoV Consensus Mechanism \]

#### **2.5.2. Proof of Range**

Proof of Range is required to establish the computational capacity to order the transactions from the Cuckoo Hash based DAG Mempool. it will be constructed using a zero knowledge proof based approach. We will be using a layered and dependency proof system based on SNARKs for our implementation. 

SNARKs, stands for Succinct Non-interactive Arguments of Knowledge. They are cryptographic protocols that allow one party (the prover) to convince another party (the verifier) that they possess a certain piece of information (the witness) without revealing the information itself.  Unlike traditional cryptographic proofs, SNARKs generate proofs that are significantly smaller ( succinct in size ). 

Layered SNARKs generate proofs that are significantly smaller than the actual computation being proven, similar to other SNARK systems. Unlike traditional SNARKs where proof size grows with circuit size, layered SNARKs produce proofs of constant size regardless of the circuit complexity, improving efficiency for large computations. Verification of proofs in layered SNARKs can be partitioned and performed layer by layer, potentially enhancing efficiency compared to verifying a single large proof in traditional SNARKs. This will be quite suitable for verifying the range proofs generated from the Cuckoo Hash based DAG Mempool. Layered SNARKs utilize a modular design, allowing complex computations to be broken down into smaller, more manageable sub-circuits within each layer. This enhances the expressiveness of the system and enables the proof of various functionalities. Layered SNARKs support recursive proofs, allowing proofs within one layer to reference and utilize proofs generated in previous layers, enabling the verification of even more complex relationships and computations. The leader node will verify the Range Proofs. 

#### **2.5.3. Proof of Randomness**

Proof of Randomness from the Cuckoo Hash based DAG Mempool will be generated using Verifiable Delay Functions (VDF). We will set up a VDF based randomness beacon that periodically generates verifiable randomness. We will leverage the Cuckoo Hashes of specific nodes or edges of the DAGs in the Mempool with unique properties. A subset of the beacon outputs will be selected based on the hash values in the specific range. The Cuckoo Hash of the DAG will be used to identify specific state transitions within the DAG that warrants VDF computations. The Cuckoo Hash of the DAG can be used to identify specific updates within the DAG that warrant VDF computations. The proofs of these computations, along with the DAG state updates and the corresponding Cuckoo Hashes, will contribute to the overall proof of randomness required to generate the Shuffle Shards.

A Verifiable Delay Function consists of three algorithms: Setup, Eval, and Verify. The Setup algorithm initializes the system with public parameters based on a security parameter and a delay parameter. The Eval algorithm processes an input to produce an output and an optional proof within a specified range. The Verify algorithm confirms the correctness of the output and proof. Key properties of a VDF include:

* Sequential computation: It requires a defined number of sequential steps to compute the output, making it resistant to acceleration by parallel processing.  
* Efficient verification: The verification process is quick, taking time proportional to the polylogarithm of the delay parameter.  
* Uniqueness: It is computationally hard to find any output that can be verified as correct for a given input, other than the one produced by the Eval algorithm.

Additionally, VDFs may possess other desirable traits:

* Decodability: Some VDFs can be decoded back into their original input without loss, making them useful for encoding schemes.  
* Incrementality: They can support multiple hardness parameters with a single set of public parameters, offering benefits like reduced proof size, which is advantageous for applications in computational time-stamping or blockchain consensus.

#### **2.5.4. Homomorphic Time Lock Puzzles**

Homomorphic Time-Lock Puzzles (HTLPs) are a cryptographic primitive that allows you to encrypt messages and ensure they can only be decrypted after a certain amount of time has elapsed, even for computationally powerful adversaries. Let us try to understand the basic notion of time locks before delving into HTLPs. 

Time-lock puzzles are cryptographic tools designed for encrypting messages so that they can only be decrypted after a specified duration, denoted by a hardness parameter   
***T***. Upon providing a secret ***s*** and ***T***, a puzzle is generated, allowing ***s*** to be recoverable only after time ***T***. These puzzles have two key features:

**Fast Puzzle Generation**: The creation of a puzzle is significantly quicker than the time required to unlock it (***T***), which is essential for secrets meant to remain hidden over long periods (e.g., 10 years).

**Security Against Parallel Algorithms**: They secure the secrets against any computational effort that does not meet the time threshold ***T***, regardless of the computational resources available. This is a nuanced form of security that ensures the puzzle cannot be solved faster through parallel processing, contrasting with traditional security measures that may be vulnerable to such approaches.

HTLPs allow you to create a "puzzle" that contains a message and a specific "lock time." Anyone can see the puzzle, but only someone who possesses the "solution" (generated when the puzzle is created) can decrypt the message after the lock time has elapsed. This unique property allows performing operations on encrypted puzzles without needing to decrypt them first. You can combine multiple puzzles, perform calculations on them, and obtain a new puzzle that decrypts to the combined result after the individual lock times of the original puzzles have elapsed. Homomorphic Time-Lock Puzzles offer a powerful cryptographic primitive with unique functionalities for securing data and controlling access based on time. 

Each observer Node attempts to solve the time-lock puzzle, which is a cryptographic puzzle requiring a specific amount of computational effort to solve. By solving the time lock puzzles, the observer nodes will be providing the proof that they have observed the leader election and density proof generation activities. 

#### **2.5.5. Advantages of PoV**

**The proof of visibility will be the combination of range proofs, randomness proofs, and time lock puzzles combined together. Range proofs establish the computational capacity to order the transactions. Randomness proofs demonstrate the computational capacity to randomize the transactions. Visibility proofs are the ratio of randomness proofs generated for every range proof in a specific time lock puzzle execution. Thus, visibility proofs are the manifestation of the density of transactions in the Cuckoo Hash based DAG Mempool. Thus the visibility proofs can be considered as the reflection of data density proofs or intent intensity proofs.** 

### **2.6. Ephemeral State Sharding Implementation**

One of the major novelties of our protocol will be the implementation of Shuffle Sharding and State Sharding in a coherent and convergent manner[^9]. This will be the first blockchain protocol to implement Shuffle Sharding for blockchain infrastructure. VRF based Shuffle Shards will be created using the ephemeral states computed using Verkle Trees. Hence our sharding technique is the confluence of Verifiable Random Functions and Verkle Trees. The ephemeral states are time transitive states created using verkle trees based on the visibility proofs and time locks derived in the consensus phase. 

#### **2.6.1. What is State Sharding?** 

*State sharding is a scalability solution that divides the blockchain state into smaller, more manageable pieces or "shards." Each shard contains a portion of the state and handles transactions independently. This division allows for parallel processing of transactions, significantly increasing the network's throughput. However, managing the state across shards while ensuring data availability[^10] and integrity poses significant challenges.*

#### **2.6.2. Ephemeral State Sharding :**

Ephemeral State Sharding involves dividing the blockchain state (all data) into horizontal partitions (shards) to improve scalability through ephemeral state computations. Unlike static sharding, ephemeral sharding allows data to be moved in between shards based on ephemeral patterns. Ephemeral states would be generated leveraging time lock batches from the proof of visibility based consensus stage. In dynamic state sharding approaches, data movement between shards introduces challenges as ensuring the overall consistency of the global state across all shards becomes a challenge. This challenge is addressed by introducing temporal order through time lock batches. 

#### **2.6.3. Verkle Tries for Ephemeral State Generation** 

A Verkle tree (short for "Vector commitment Merkle tree") is a type of cryptographic data structure that builds upon the concept of Merkle trees to offer additional security and efficiency benefits. *Verkle trees are emerging as a crucial component in the scaling strategies for Ethereum, offering functionality similar to that of Merkle trees. They allow the encapsulation of large amounts of data within a tree structure, facilitating the creation of concise proofs ("witnesses") for any single piece or set of data pieces. These proofs can be verified by someone possessing only the tree's root. The distinguishing feature of Verkle trees is their efficiency in proof size; for instance, a proof for data within a billion-piece tree would only require less than 150 bytes in a Verkle tree, compared to about 1 kilobyte in a traditional binary Merkle tree. This efficiency makes the implementation of stateless clients practically feasible.*

*The structure of Verkle trees closely resembles that of the Merkle Patricia trees used in Ethereum, where each node can be empty, a leaf node with a key-value pair, or an intermediate node with a fixed number of children (defined by the tree's "width"). The value of an intermediate node is derived from hashing its children's values. However, Verkle trees differ by having a much wider structure, which contributes to shorter proof lengths as the tree width increases, though at the cost of longer proof creation times for very wide trees.* Verkle trees leverage their structure and cryptographic properties to generate more compact proofs. Membership proofs only require including a constant number of elements (usually logarithmic to the number of elements) along the path. *However, they do introduce a higher computational load for creating and verifying proofs, due to the complexity of computing polynomial expressions and commitments.* 

![][image13]  
\[Figure 13\.  Verkle Trees\]

*Verkle trees play a crucial role in the implementation of ephemeral state sharding by providing a compact, efficient structure for representing and verifying the state across shards, including ephemeral ones. Here's how Verkle trees contribute to this process:*

* ***Efficient State Representation**: Verkle trees allow for a succinct representation of the state, even as it is divided among multiple shards. This is critical in ephemeral sharding, where the state's structure may frequently change as shards are created and disbanded.*  
* ***Proof Efficiency**: With Verkle trees, proving the existence or value of a state variable within any shard requires significantly smaller proofs than traditional Merkle trees. This efficiency is particularly beneficial in a sharded system, where cross-shard communication and verification might otherwise introduce bottlenecks.*  
* ***Dynamic Sharding Compatibility**: The use of Verkle trees in ephemeral sharding supports the dynamic nature of shard creation and dissolution. Since Verkle trees can efficiently handle changes to the state with minimal proof sizes, they are well-suited to the fluid structure of ephemeral shards.*  
* ***Statelessness and Data Availability**: Verkle trees contribute to a stateless or near-stateless blockchain model, where nodes do not need to store the entire state to participate in validation. This characteristic is essential for ephemeral state sharding, ensuring that nodes can quickly adapt to changes in shard composition without the overhead of managing a complete state.*  
* ***Cross-Shard Transactions**: The compact proofs provided by Verkle trees facilitate easier verification of cross-shard transactions, a critical requirement for the seamless operation of a sharded blockchain. This ensures that even as the state is temporarily divided, the integrity and continuity of transactions across shards are maintained.*

*Verkle trees represent a forward-looking approach to scaling blockchain networks. This method aims to enhance the network's capacity and performance by dividing the state into temporary, manageable shards as Verkle trees enable efficient state representation and verification. The ephemeral nature of these shards helps in managing the blockchain's state more flexibly and efficiently, adapting to varying network loads without permanently segmenting the state.*

*Here's a simplified explanation of how it works:*  
 *\* Sharding: The Ethereum state is split into horizontal slices called shards. Each shard processes a subset of transactions.*  
 *\* Verkle Tries: Instead of storing the entire state in each shard, only a compressed summary using Verkle trees is kept. This summary allows verifying the validity of any state element without needing the entire state.*  
 *\* State Verification: When a node needs to verify a state element, it retrieves the relevant proof from the Verkle tree. This proof can be cryptographically verified to ensure the element's authenticity and inclusion in the original state.*  
*Verkle trees offer several advantages for dynamic state sharding:*  
 *\* Scalability: By storing compressed state summaries, Verkle trees reduce storage requirements for shard validators, improving scalability.*  
 *\* Efficiency: Verkle tree proofs enable efficient verification of state elements, reducing the computational burden on validators.*  
 *\* Security: Verkle trees maintain the security of the Ethereum state by allowing cryptographic verification of state elements.*

#### **2.6.3. Shuffle Sharding[^11] :** 

*This technique diversifies and distributes payloads by combining them into probabilistic and randomized shards, thus preventing the chance of deterministic and distributed attacks on the infrastructure.* 

*![][image14]*

\[Figure 14 : Work Flow of Shuffle Sharding\]

#### **2.6.4. VRFs(Verifiable Random Functions)**

VRFs are cryptographic primitives that offer a unique combination of randomness and verifiability. They allow a party to generate a random value while proving that the generation process was fair and untampered with. This verification is crucial in blockchain applications where trust is paramount.

Here's how VRFs work:

1. Input: A VRF takes an arbitrary input, such as a transaction or validator ID.  
2. Random Output: The VRF generates a seemingly random output value for the given input.  
3. Proof Generation: The VRF also produces a cryptographic proof that demonstrably links the output to the original input.  
4. Verification: Anyone can verify the proof, ensuring the randomness of the output and that it was correctly computed from the claimed input.

This combination of randomness and verifiability makes VRFs ideal for shuffle sharding.

Shuffle sharding leverages VRFs to create a more robust and secure sharding approach. 

1. Transaction Submission: A user submits a transaction to the blockchain network.  
2. VRF Evaluation: Each validator node independently runs the VRF on the transaction data.  
3. Shuffling: The VRF outputs from all validators are combined using a cryptographic function. This "shuffling" process obscures the original VRF outputs and ensures the final shard assignments are unpredictable.  
4. Shard Assignment: Based on the shuffled output and a predefined mapping function, a specific shard is assigned to the transaction.  
5. Transaction Delivery: The transaction is then routed to the designated shard for validation and execution.

Benefits of VRFs in Shuffle Sharding:

* Fairness: VRFs guarantee that the shuffling process is unbiased and verifiable. This prevents malicious actors from manipulating transaction distribution across shards and gaining an unfair advantage.  
* Security: Since the VRF function is verifiable, validators cannot tamper with the shuffling process or assign transactions to their preferred shards. This strengthens the overall security of the sharded network.  
* Improved Load Balancing: The randomness introduced by VRFs helps distribute transactions more evenly across shards, leading to better load balancing and overall network performance.

#### **2.6.5. Integrated Approach :**

*The realization of VRF based shuffle sharding and Verkle Tree based ephemeral state sharding offers a sophisticated framework for blockchain networks. This combination helps Vision Chain to achieve data sharding and state sharding in a coherent and convergent manner.* Verkle trees facilitate this process by efficiently generating the state across these shuffled shards. Since Verkle trees allow for compact representation and verification of state, they are well-suited to handle the increased dynamism introduced by shuffle sharding in an ephemeral environment. 

### **2.7. Dynamic Accumulator based zkVM implementation**

Our zkVM implementation will be focused on providing optimum performance of the ephemeral state shards created through the proof of visibility consensus. As we are implementing ephemeral state sharding, we will be adopting a [dynamic accumulator](https://eprint.iacr.org/2018/1188.pdf)[^12] model in the state machine. This requires efficient addition and removal from the set. Thus, our zkVM State Machine will be based on dynamic cryptographic accumulators invented by [Dan Boneh, Benedikt Bunz, and Ben Fisch[^13].](https://eprint.iacr.org/2018/1188.pdf)  

Accumulators allow for proving that an element belongs to a set without revealing the entire set or the element itself. This is achieved by creating a short "proof" that can be verified efficiently. Accumulators compress information about a large set into a single, small value. This makes them significantly more space-efficient compared to storing the entire set explicitly.

In zkVMs, proving the validity of the entire machine state for every transaction can be computationally expensive. Dynamic accumulators can be used to efficiently prove that a specific state element belongs to the valid global state, without revealing all details of the state. Dynamic accumulators can help generate concise zero-knowledge proofs for zkVMs, reducing communication overhead and improving scalability. By only revealing membership information for specific state elements, dynamic accumulators can offer some level of privacy for the overall zkVM state. 

Accumulators can be used to efficiently prove that a specific state or transaction belongs to the valid state history of the zkVM. This is crucial for ensuring the validity of proofs submitted to the mainnet. For example, an accumulator can be used to store all valid transaction hashes, and a prover can demonstrate that a particular transaction hash is included, without revealing the entire transaction data. This reduces the amount of data that needs to be sent to the mainnet for verification. Thus it can provide efficient membership proofs.  In zkVM, accumulators can be used to prove that the inclusion of a specific state transition is within a large batch of ephemeral shard state computations. It will also be useful to verify the validity of transactions without revealing all transaction data in the zk-proof. 

By using membership proofs for state transitions and transactions, zk-proofs can become more compact, improving scalability.  Verifying membership proofs in accumulators is often less computationally expensive compared to verifying the entire computation in the zk-proof, leading to faster verification on the main chain. A dynamic accumulator can track the entire state of the zkVM. Membership proofs can then be used to prove the validity of specific state transitions within a batch. Dynamic accumulators hold promise for building more scalable and efficient zkVMs. By leveraging their ability to provide succinct proofs for state membership, zkVMs can achieve faster verification times and potentially improve overall system performance.

### **2.8. Homomorphic Hashing[^14] based Data Availability Approach**

In a modular blockchain architecture, a data availability layer plays a crucial role in ensuring that information relevant to the blockchain's state and transactions is accessible to the network participants. It is responsible for securely storing the data associated with the blockchain. This includes transaction data, and smart contract states. We are following an established technique known as data availability samping. 

Data Availability Sampling (DAS) is a technique that allows participants of a network to ensure the full availability of some data without any participant downloading it entirely. A DAS scheme should satisfy three main properties. First, it should be complete, such that the verifiers having valid commitment and probing a valid encoding should successfully conclude that the encoded data is fully available. Second, it should be sound such that enough successful probes to the encoding for recovering some data segment. Third, a DAS scheme should provide consistency for a fixed but possibly malformed commitment such that one can recover at least one unique data segment. 

#### **2.8.1. Homomorphic Hashing \- An Introduction**

*Homomorphic hashing is a sophisticated method for ensuring data-integrity, privacy and scalability. Unlike traditional hashing, which is a one-way process to generate a fixed-size output from any size input, homomorphic hashing allows for certain computations to be carried out on the hash values themselves, mirroring operations on the original data*

*Homomorphic hashing is a cryptographic primitive that allows for operations to be performed on the hash values of data in a way that mirrors operations performed on the data itself. This means that given the hash of some data, certain operations (like addition or multiplication) can be performed directly on the hash without needing access to the original data. The result of such operations on the hash can then be compared to the hash of the result of the same operations performed on the original data. If they match, it implies that the operations on the original data were performed correctly.*

Homomorphic hashing functions are used to transform data into a compact binary representation, called a "homomorphic hash," that can be easily verified without revealing any information about the original data. Data availability sampling often requires randomly checking parts of a dataset to ensure it is fully available and has not been tampered with. Homomorphic hashing can enable efficient verification of these samples. Since operations can be performed on hashes, it reduces the need for large amounts of data to be transferred and verified, making the sampling process faster and less resource-intensive. It is also important to note that homomorphic hashing allows the nodes to ensure that data blocks are complete and unaltered before being added to a blockchain.

#### **2.8.2. Homomorphic Hashing and Data Availability Sampling**

The ordered data generated by the proof of visibility sequencer module is divided into fragments (shards). Erasure codes are applied to the fragments, generating additional redundant information (parity bits or other codes) along with the original fragments. This allows reconstructing the original data even if some fragments are lost. These fragments and the additional information are collectively called coded blocks. A homomorphic hash function is applied to each coded block. This generates a hash value that mathematically represents the content of the coded block while preserving specific homomorphic properties. The hash values are committed to the settlement network, which is a distributed ledger. This ensures the integrity and immutability of the recorded information. Anyone can verify the availability of the data by downloading the hash values from the settlement layer by selecting a random subset of coded blocks or by recalculating the homomorphic hash of the selected coded blocks using the original homomorphic hash function or by verifying if the recalculated hash values match the ones stored on the blockchain.

The homomorphic property allows performing certain operations on the encrypted data (represented by the hash values) without needing to download and decrypt the actual coded blocks. This saves bandwidth and computational resources for verifiers. For example, to verify the availability of multiple coded blocks, the verifier can add the corresponding hash values downloaded from the settlement layer, and then compare the sum with the homomorphic sum of the hash functions applied to the selected coded blocks they downloaded. This leverages the homomorphic addition property to efficiently verify the availability of multiple data pieces without needing the entire dataset.

This approach allows verifying data availability without downloading the entire dataset, making it suitable for large amounts of data stored on blockchains. Homomorphic properties enable efficient verification by performing operations on the compact hash values instead of the full data. The immutability of the blockchain ensures the integrity of the stored hash values, preventing tampering with the data availability proofs.

#### **2.8.2.Technical Considerations**

* *Choice of Homomorphic Hash Function: The specific properties of the homomorphic hash function (e.g., whether it supports additive or multiplicative operations, or both) will influence how it can be used within a Layer 2 protocol. The function must be chosen carefully to balance computational efficiency with security requirements. eg: Fully Homomorphic functions, Paillier Encrypto-system[^15] etc.*  
* *Security Assumptions: The security of homomorphic hashing based data availability relies on the cryptographic strength of the hash function. It must be resistant to collisions (where two different inputs produce the same hash) and preimage attacks (determining the input from the hash). (Quantum resistance to be kept in mind).*   
* *Interoperability: For cross chain/ cross rollup solutions. the use of homomorphic hashing must be compatible across different systems. This requires standardization of cryptographic primitives and protocols.*   
* *Considering these perspectives, we will be leveraging [LtHash](https://github.com/nicolagiacchetta/lthash)[^16], a Lattice Cryptography based implementation of Homomorphic Hashing. .*

#### **2.8.4. Quantum resistance with Homomorphic Hash Functions**

**Lattice-Based Homomorphic Hashing**: Lattice-based cryptography is considered one of the most promising areas for quantum-resistant cryptographic schemes. Homomorphic hashing methodologies based on lattice problems could offer inherent resistance to quantum attacks. These schemes benefit from the hard lattice problems that remain computationally difficult for quantum computers.

### **2.9. zkProver**

zkProver is a core component within the zkVM framework. All the proof generation and verification transactions are handled by the zkProver. Hence the rules for the transaction validity are enforced by zkProver. We are following a state machine model for the zkProver inspired by its simplicity and elegance. This will align well with our overall zkVM design.

zkProver system in Vision Chain is used to generate the proofs related to the interoperability layer,  range proofs and randomness proofs in the observer nodes, and the density proofs in the leader nodes.  Thus zkProver interacts with the Interoperability services, Leader Nodes, Observer Nodes and the Proof Databases of the protocol infrastructure. 

#### **2.9.1. Basics**

zkProver generates the zero-knowledge proofs for transactions, state transitions or smart contract executions within the zkVM. It performs this by taking the inputs of a confirmed block of transaction coming from the sequencer, processing them according to the rules defined in the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM), and then generating a proof that certifies the correctness of these computations without revealing the inputs or the immediate states of the computation. The zkProver trusts the final block states proposed by the shared sequencer network coming through the PoV consensus, hence their proof generated will convey:

1. Proofs regarding the state transitions resulting in execution of the transactions in the block.  
2. Proofs regarding the validators themselves reaching a consensus on the chain of blocks.

#### **2.9.2. Benefits**

* **Privacy**: By enabling transactions and smart contract executions to be verified without revealing their contents, zkProver significantly enhances privacy on the blockchain.  
* **Scalability**: By aggregating multiple transactions into a single proof, zkProver can greatly reduce the blockchain's storage and processing requirements, leading to increased throughput and reduced transaction fees.  
* **Interoperability**: zkProver's compatibility with the Ethereum Virtual Machine makes it a powerful tool for integrating zero-knowledge proofs into existing blockchain applications and ecosystems without extensive modifications.

### **2.11. zkProver in Vision Chain**

zkSTARKs can be used to develop proofs of data density and data availability.

 \* Proofs of data density: zkSTARKs can be used to prove that a particular dataset contains a certain amount of information without revealing the actual content of the data. This can be useful for verifying that a cloud storage provider is actually storing the data they claim to be storing.  
 \* Proofs of data availability: zkSTARKs can also be used to prove that a particular piece of data is available at a specific location. This can be useful for ensuring that data hasn't been tampered with or deleted. Then we can use it for range proofs required in the proof of visibility

zkSTARKs can be used in zkVMs. In fact, one prominent zkVM implementation, StarkNet, leverages zkSTARKs for its proof system. zkSTARKs offer several advantages in this context, including:  
 \* Security: They are considered theoretically more secure than zk-SNARKs, another common zero-knowledge proof system.  
 \* Scalability: They are well-suited for handling large numbers of transactions, which is crucial for zkVMs aiming to achieve high throughput.  
However, zkSTARKs also come with some drawbacks:  
 \* Computational Cost: Generating zkSTARK proofs can be more computationally expensive compared to zk-SNARKs.  
 \* Proof Size: The proofs themselves tend to be larger, leading to higher storage requirements.  
Overall, zkSTARKs are a viable option for zkVMs, particularly those prioritizing security and scalability.

### **2.12 Multi Party Machine Learning Oracles**

Traditional oracles act as bridges between blockchains and the external world, feeding data from external sources onto the blockchain. However, they can introduce centralization risks if controlled by a single entity. Through Multi Party Machine Learning (MPML) oracles, we are aiming to open up the gateways of blockchain to ingest and integrate a wide spectrum of data sets in a comprehensive manner. 

MPML Oracles are designed to compute the dynamics of data using the creative convergence of multi party computation methods and privacy preserving machine learning models using federated learning and meta learning frameworks.  Thus our approach can be considered as a multi party machine learning framework through which real world datasets will become verified and validated data streams. The streams of data from all the sources will be integrated into the multi party machine learning framework that computes the trust factor from the data in a continuous manner. 

MPML Oracles can aggregate and compute inferences and patterns from data feeds for anomalies flagging attempts to manipulate data for malicious purposes. MPML Oracles can also gather data from various sources and cross reference them, reducing reliance on a single source and minimizing the risk of inaccuracies.  

MPC allows parties to perform computations on data keeping the data private. It facilitates training and execution of machine learning models on private data sets owned by different parties, enabling the evaluation of one party’s private model using another party’s private data. 

MPC programs rely on building blocks like Boolean (AND/OR) and arithmetic (ADD/MULT) circuits to perform any kind of calculation. These circuits are like blueprints for the computations. Since MPC needs to ensure secrecy, secure protocols are established specifically for addition and multiplication operations. To achieve this security, MPC often works using finite fields. Additionally, most MPC tools require a separate program to translate regular code into these special arithmetic circuits**.**

The initial set of federated learning models decipher the patterns from the raw datasets. The privacy preserving multi party machine learning models infer the coherence and credibility of data through benchmarking the performance and parity of each model together with the datasets.

Alice wants to send 1 token-b to Bob. At this time, there is no need to repurchase and back up NC-b to send token-b.  When Alice sends an intent for bToken transmission to the Vision AI network, it sends it to the shared sequencer of the node connected to network a and uses it as GAS free in real time, and it sends it to the shared sequencer of the node connected to network b to generate multiple rollups and pass them to the pool. Data sent to a mempool through a shared sequence is automatically verified by the Sharding node, and the node processes the transaction, including the intent, at each layer. At this time, the details of the transaction are open to both the prioritization role and the participants, while the details are not open to the public, so it checks the visibility of 'I have seen it' and creates and stores the block. At the same time, to support this task, the Vision AI DE-Fi system automatically calculates the equivalent quantity of NC-a's gas on network a, and as a result, the quantity of NC-a is shifted to SwapPool provided by Vision AI, the gas is paid to NC-b, and token-b is sent to the recipient's wallet address. As a result, Alice paid NC-b to send Token-b.  |
| Ethereum is required as a Native Coin to transfer the ERC-20 token. Solana is required as a Native Coin to transmit SPL tokens.  | Any Native Coin must be used to transfer the ERC-20 token, and any layer issued token can be used as Gas Fee through Custom Gas Tokens powered by account abstraction.   |

### **4.2.PoV vs PoS and PoW**

|  | PoV | PoS / PoA | PoW |

| Support for Single Secret Leader Election | Powered by Single Secret Leader Election that is efficient and economical. The generation of Re-Randomizable Commitments offer better economic efficiency and security. | Stake based Consensus where a large network of validators are required.   | Computational Power based Consensus where a large network of miners required to contribute their hashing power. |
| Support for  | Consensus based on the ability of nodes to provide the proof of capacity to do computation sharding and state sharding | Consensus is not designed to support the creation of shards. | Consensus is not designed to support the creation of shards. |
| Energy Efficiency  | Combination of Low Intensity and High Intensity Components Integrated in a modular fashion | Medium | High-intensive |
| Scalability  | Highly Scalable through Mempool and Sharding Technique Implementation | Better than PoW  | Requires time to complete the mining process |
| Decentralization  | Fairly decentralized | Can lead to centralization in terms of wealth and staked amount | Can lead to centralization in terms of compute power |
| Validator Requirements | Combination of Active and Passive Validators make the consensus versatile | Wealth concentration can lead to unfair decisions. | Possibility for compromise as larger mining pools can dominate the network |
| Consensus Finality  | Immediate Soft Finality through Proof of Visibility and Eventual Finality through Accumulated State Proofs | Deterministic finality | Not immediate |
| Network Latency and Throughput | Low Latency through High Speed Mempool and Proof of Visibility Consensus  | Low Latency | High latency |
| Upgrade Processes | Dynamic Upgrade through Modular Architecture | Dynamic | Requires agreement from the entire community |
| Implementation Difficulty  | Modular Approach. Hence incremental implementation of complex components.  | Gets complex according to the variants chosen. | Complex |
| Cross-Chain/Cross-Rollup Interaction Ease | Interactions are made easily | Bridges required. | Bridges required. |
| Security Model \- resistance to attacks |   | based on economic stakes. More resistant to 51% attack. | Maintained through computational work. Vulnerable to 51% attack. |
| Accessibility and Fairness among network Participants | Better reward opportunities for network participants | Provided they have stake, only they can participate. | Should have access to high compute power to participate. |
| Participation Incentives |  | Earns based on the staked amount. Predictable returns. | Fluctuate with network difficulty and energy costs |
| Ease of entry for new network participants |  | Requires funds to own native currency coins. | High barrier due to the need of specialized mining hardware. |

## **5\. Technical Architecture**

| Network Layer Protocol : Vision Chain employs a decentralized and dynamic shared sequencer network for transaction ordering and transaction finality.  Node Infrastructure : Nodes maintain the blockchain, verify transactions, and achieve consensus. Consensus Layer Algorithm : Vision Chain uses PoV to ensure agreement on the blockchain state. Validator Management : Leader Nodes acts as Validators, They validate blocks, incentivized through token rewards. Smart Contract Layer zkVM Platform : Vision Chain uses a zkVM powered smart contracts, namely Dynamic Accumulator zkVM (dazkVM) Contracts : Developers create diverse smart contracts for De-Fi, Gaming, NFTs, and etc. Data Storage Layer Database : Vision Chain utilizes a shuffle sharded distributed database (DHT or P2P) for decentralized data management. Indexing : Implements data indexing techniques for efficient querying. User Interface Layer Wallets : Users interact through web mobile or hardware wallets for token management and smart contract interactions. dApps :  Developers create decentralized applications for various purposes. Security Layer Cryptography : Advanced techniques like zero-knowledge proofs, single secret leader election, homomorphic hashing, etc.  enhance privacy and security. Protocols : Implements Lattice Cryptography for homomorphic hashing and access control. Blockchain Analytics Layer Explorer : Vision AI offers a blockchain explorer for transaction and smart contract data. Analytics Tools : Provides tools for developers and users to analyze blockchain data and identify trends.  | ![][image21] |
| :---- | :---- |

This Vision AI technical architecture ensures a robust, scalable, and secure platform for decentralized applications , prioritizing user experience and privacy.

## **6\. Conclusion**

As mentioned in the introduction, vision chain is an ensemble of state of the art protocols and principles surrounding the world of blockchains. It is designed with a holistic vision on the historic premises of distributed systems, contemporary currents of decentralized applications and future trajectories of self sovereign systems. From the first interaction to the final integration, Vision Chain protects the user identity and transaction integrity through the convergence of cryptographic constructions.
